HARARE A former Zimbabwean government chief buyer allegedly committed suicide by jumping from a building in Harare on Tuesday.Former State Procurement Board (SPB) chairman Charles Kuwaza is said to have jumped from the ninth floor of Harare Club Chambers in the capital city's central business district.The building is located diagonally opposite Parliament Building, at the corner of Third Street and Nelson Mandela Avenue.No official details could be obtained and even a relative, who requested anonymity, responded to African News Agency that: [I] don t have full details as yet. READ: Mugabe urges Zimbabweans to guard their independenceIt was said Kuwaza had gone to the building to collect documents to help with his defence in a court matter.He was facing five counts of corruption involving $1-million (R13.3-million) and ZW$2.5-billion.In March, Kuwaza was freed on US$2,000 bail.ANA heard that the former SPB boss went to his office at about 11am accompanied by his wife, who remained in the car downstairs as Kuwaza went up to his office.His lifeless body was found on the tarmac almost an hour later,READ: Facebook murder suspect found deadThe SPB is the government s buying entity, which previously was tasked with fighting tenders and awarding them to winners, before the Office of the President took over the process, citing massive irregularities at the government buying arm.Kuwaza, who had been at the helm of the SPB since the early 2000s, was kicked out of the government buying entity in November 2015 after being accused of violating professional ethics by allegedly awarding tenders to companies that did not meet specifications.He denied the charges, admitting in 2012 before the parliamentary portfolio committee on budget and finance that the SPB had corrupt officers who opened tenders and phoned bidders demanding bribes to facilitate winning . African News Agency